Consults with users to identify current cyber security services operating procedures, problems, and requirements. Designs models and utilizes analysis and security solution development methods, including process maps, flow charts, diagrams, situational awareness and incident response, secure web hosting, and backups. Scopes project costs and timelines. Documents installation, maintenance, and cyber security operating procedures. May create coding and logic specifications for developers. Coordinate with Government Task Manager and/or COR, and other project personnel for specific project requirements and schedule via informal discussions, scheduled meetings, and established in-process reviews. The Contractor shall provide a Web analytics service (SiteGauge or equivalent) based upon log file analysis (e.g., site sessions, page views) and JavaScript tracking using best industry standards to designated users for each web site, and other support tasks as directed by the COR. Provide a Web based analytics front-end package that supports the collection of specific data points: number of visits, unique visitors, visit duration, authenticated users, organic search terms, domains, countries, cities, IP addresses, hosts lists, last visits and unresolved IP lists, and virus detection.

raw_data.title: Cyber Security Engineer
raw_data.description: Cyber Security Engineer plans and designs security solutions and capabilities that enable the organization to identify, protect, detect, respond, and recover from cyber threats and vulnerabilities. Defines and develops security requirements using risk assessments, threat modeling, testing, and analysis of existing systems. Develops security integration plans to protect existing infrastructure and to incorporate future solutions. Designs action plans for policy creation and governance, network management, security system hardening, monitoring, situational awareness and incident response, disaster recovery, and emerging cybersecurity threats. Partners with stakeholders to encourage the adoption of security-compatible software designs and best practices. Keeps abreast of the latest intelligence from law enforcement and other sources of cyber threat information. Manage and secure the DMA-Web.mil infrastructure to ensure all Web products and support delivered by the organization are compliant with all federal laws, DoD policies & general security best practices. Additionally, and more specifically, although not an exhaustive list, are those recurring cybersecurity tasks with respect to incident response, OPORD/TASKER compliance, ACAS, HBSS, VDPs, PPSM, DMZ NIPRNet Whitelist, application canning & security, threat logs/customer access support, 8570 Workforce Improvement, POA&Ms, RAMs, and Accreditations for AFPIMS, and any other Web Enterprise Business initiatives. Support the IAM in the development of security related plans, policies, and procedures, and support implementation of these mechanisms and processes. Perform contingency planning and operations for activities consistent with the requirements in NIST 800-34 Rev. 5 for all applicable security controls, in order to obtain, and maintain an authority to operate. Responsible for DMA a complete accreditation package to include cyber security services like System Security Plan, Security Assessment Report, any applicable Plans of Action & Milestones (POA&M), Disaster Recovery Plan, Spillage Handling, and other documents as required by the NIST RMF, and overlaid DoD requirements, to support validation and Authority To Operate (ATO) activities on premises, and in the commercial (or government) cloud environments. Provide cyber security monitoring, to include but not limited to the review of logs, alerts, and system vulnerabilities identified both internally, and from sources external to DMA, to include, but not limited to the DoD Vulnerability Disclosure Program.
